reason.tex:
%text Imagine a task (like flipping a coin) that could either be a success (getting heads) or a failure (getting tails).
If this task is done $n$ times, then what is the probability of getting $r$ successes?
As can be seen from the table below, this is \underline\text{also a probability distribtution}. But it has a special name - \underline\text{binomial distribution}
% \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|} \hline r & 0 & 1 & \ldots & n \\ \hline P(r) & p_0 & p_1 & \ldots & p_n \\ \hline \end{tabular}
%text
In particular \[ P(r) = ^nC_r\cdot p^r\cdot q^{(n-r)}\] where \[ q = 1-p \] %
